# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: systems-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] A **biological network** is a method of representing systems as complex sets of binary interactions or relations between various biological entities.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In general, networks or graphs are used to capture relationships between entities or objects.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] A network can be represented as an N×N matrix where N is the number of nodes, and whose entries tell you if two nodes share an edge.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Typically, this matrix will have entries of 0 or 1 with 1 denoting an edge.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] We can optionally use a weighted graph by assigning a weight to each edge to show how relevant the connection between two nodes is.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] As early as 1736 Leonhard Euler analyzed a real-world issue known as the Seven Bridges of Königsberg, which established the foundation of graph theory.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] From the 1930s-1950s the study of random graphs were developed.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] During the mid-1990s, it was discovered that many different types of "real" networks have structural properties quite different from random networks.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In the late 2000s, scale-free and small-world networks began shaping the emergence of systems biology, network biology, and network medicine.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In 2014, graph theoretical methods were used by Frank Emmert-Streib to analyze biological networks.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In the 1980s, researchers started viewing DNA or genomes as the dynamic storage of a language system with precise computable finite states represented as a finite-state machine.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Recent complex systems research has also suggested some far-reaching commonality in the organization of information in problems from biology, computer science, and physics.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Many international efforts have resulted in databases that catalog experimentally determined protein-protein interactions.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Some of them are the Human Protein Reference Database, Database of Interacting Proteins, the Molecular Interaction Database (MINT), IntAct, and BioGRID.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] At the same time, multiple computational approaches have been proposed to predict interactions.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] FunCoup and STRING are examples of such databases, where protein-protein interactions inferred from multiple evidences are gathered and made available for public usage.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Recent studies have indicated the conservation of molecular networks through deep evolutionary time.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Moreover, it has been discovered that proteins with high degrees of connectedness are more likely to be essential for survival than proteins with lesser degrees.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] This observation suggests that the overall composition of the network (not simply interactions between protein pairs) is vital for an organism's overall functioning.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The genome encodes thousands of genes whose products (mRNAs, proteins) are crucial to the various processes of life, such as cell differentiation, cell survival, and metabolism.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Genes produce such products through a process called transcription, which is regulated by a class of proteins called transcription factors.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] For instance, the human genome encodes almost 1,500 DNA-binding transcription factors that regulate the expression of more than 20,000 human genes.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The complete set of gene products and the interactions among them constitutes gene regulatory networks (GRN).
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] GRNs regulate the levels of gene products within the cell and in-turn the cellular processes.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] GRNs are represented with genes and transcriptional factors as nodes and the relationship between them as edges.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] These edges are directional, representing the regulatory relationship between the two ends of the edge.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] For example, the directed edge from gene A to gene B indicates that A regulates the expression of B.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Thus, these directional edges can not only represent the promotion of gene regulation but also its inhibition.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] GRNs are usually constructed by utilizing the gene regulation knowledge available from databases such as., Reactome and KEGG.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] High-throughput measurement technologies, such as microarray, RNA-Seq, ChIP-chip, and ChIP-seq, enabled the accumulation of large-scale transcriptomics data, which could help in understanding the complex gene regulation patterns.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Gene co-expression networks can be perceived as association networks between variables that measure transcript abundances.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] These networks have been used to provide a system biologic analysis of DNA microarray data, RNA-seq data, miRNA data, etc. weighted gene co-expression network analysis is extensively used to identify co-expression modules and intramodular hub genes.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Co-expression modules may correspond to cell types or pathways, while highly connected intramodular hubs can be interpreted as representatives of their respective modules.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Within a nucleus, DNA is constantly in motion.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Perpetual actions such as genome folding and Cohesin extrusion morph the shape of a genome in real time.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The spatial location of strands of chromatin relative to each other plays an important role in the activation or suppression of certain genes.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] DNA-DNA Chromatin Networks help biologists to understand these interactions by analyzing commonalities amongst different loci.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The size of a network can vary significantly, from a few genes to several thousand and thus network analysis can provide vital support in understanding relationships among different areas of the genome.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] As an example, analysis of spatially similar loci within the organization in a nucleus with Genome Architecture Mapping (GAM) can be used to construct a network of loci with edges representing highly linked genomic regions.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In such networks, edge weights often correspond to the frequency or strength of interaction between loci, while network construction may involve filtering or thresholding to retain only strong interactions.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Some examples of this may include filtering out certain gene locations, filtering based on quartile of closeness, or by expression as this can serve to reduce noise and highlight biologically meaningful relationships for interpretation.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The first graphic portrays the layout of the Hist1 region of the mm9 mouse genome, a large cluster of genes that encode for replication-dependant histones.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The organization of the histone genes in this cluster have been found to be practically identical to that of the human Hist1 region.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The data used to develop this network graph was discovered through GAM.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Each node on the graph represents a genomic loci within the mouse genome.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The edges between the nodes represent a linkage disequilibrium between the connected nodes greater than the average across all 81 genomic windows.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The initial locations of the nodes within the graphic were randomly selected but the methodology of choosing edges shaped the graph into a rudimentary graphical representation of the placement of genomic loci throughout the Hist1 region.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Highly connected nodes in such chromatin interaction networks can be interpreted as hubs, and may be used to define communities of loci that interact more frequently with one another.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] These community structures reflect the modular organization commonly observed in biological and regulatory networks.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In hub-based approaches, nodes are assigned to the community of the hub with which they share the strongest interaction, often with constraints to ensure that each node belongs to only one community.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Such network representations are closely related to heat map visualizations, where interaction data are displayed as a matrix (adjacency matrix) in which each cell represents the interaction strength between two loci.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Patterns observed in heat maps, such as dense blocks of high interaction, often correspond to communities identified in the network representation.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] These approaches enable combination of graph-based and matrix-based analyses of chromatin organization.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] This type of comparison can be seen in the graphics below where the heat map and network visualizations can be compared in such a manner.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Cells break down the food and nutrients into small molecules necessary for cellular processing through a series of biochemical reactions.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] These biochemical reactions are catalyzed by enzymes.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The complete set of all these biochemical reactions in all the pathways represents the metabolic network.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Within the metabolic network, the small molecules take the roles of nodes, and they could be either carbohydrates, lipids, or amino acids.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The reactions which convert these small molecules from one form to another are represented as edges.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] It is possible to use network analyses to infer how selection acts on metabolic pathways.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Signals are transduced within cells or in between cells and thus form complex signaling networks which plays a key role in the tissue structure.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] For instance, the MAPK/ERK pathway is transduced from the cell surface to the cell nucleus by a series of protein-protein interactions, phosphorylation reactions, and other events.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Signaling networks typically integrate protein–protein interaction networks, gene regulatory networks, and metabolic networks.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Single cell sequencing technologies allows the extraction of inter-cellular signaling, an example is NicheNet, which allows to modeling intercellular communication by linking ligands to target genes.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The complex interactions in the brain make it a perfect candidate to apply network theory.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Neurons in the brain are deeply connected with one another, and this results in complex networks being present in the structural and functional aspects of the brain.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] For instance, small-world network properties have been demonstrated in connections between cortical regions of the primate brain or during swallowing in humans.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] This suggests that cortical areas of the brain are not directly interacting with each other, but most areas can be reached from all others through only a few interactions.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] All organisms are connected through feeding interactions.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] If a species eats or is eaten by another species, they are connected in an intricate food web of predator and prey interactions.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The stability of these interactions has been a long-standing question in ecology.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] That is to say if certain individuals are removed, what happens to the network (i.e., does it collapse or adapt)?
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Network analysis can be used to explore food web stability and determine if certain network properties result in more stable networks.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Moreover, network analysis can be used to determine how selective removals of species will influence the food web as a whole.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] This is especially important considering the potential species loss due to global climate change.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Network medicine is an emerging field that applies network principles to understand the molecular basis of human disease.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Instead of focusing on single genes or proteins, network medicine examines how diseases arise from small changes in complex biological networks, including protein-protein interaction networks, gene regulatory networks, and metabolic pathways.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Within this framework, diseases are associated with specific “disease modules,” defined as groups of interconnected components whose collective dysfunction contributes to a pathological state.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] This network based perspective enables the identification of disease associated genes, the analysis of relationships between different diseases, and the development of therapeutic strategies that target multiple components of a biological system rather than a single molecule.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Network medicine also supports approaches such as drug repurposing and the integration of large-scale omics data, providing a systems-level complement to traditional reductionist methods and contributing to advances in precision medicine.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In biology, pairwise interactions have historically been the focus of intense study.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] With the recent advances in network science, it has become possible to scale up pairwise interactions to include individuals of many species involved in many sets of interactions to understand the structure and function of larger ecological networks.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The use of network analysis can allow for both the discovery and understanding of how these complex interactions link together within the system's network, a property that has previously been overlooked.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] This powerful tool allows for the study of various types of interactions (from competitive to cooperative) using the same general framework.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] For example, plant-pollinator interactions are mutually beneficial and often involve many different species of pollinators as well as many different species of plants.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] These interactions are critical to plant reproduction and thus the accumulation of resources at the base of the food chain for primary consumers, yet these interaction networks are threatened by anthropogenic change.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The use of network analysis can illuminate how pollination networks work and may, in turn, inform conservation efforts.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Within pollination networks, nestedness (i.e., specialists interact with a subset of species that generalists interact with), redundancy (i.e., most plants are pollinated by many pollinators), and modularity play a large role in network stability.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] These network properties may actually work to slow the spread of disturbance effects through the system and potentially buffer the pollination network from anthropogenic changes somewhat.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] More generally, the structure of species interactions within an ecological network can tell us something about the diversity, richness, and robustness of the network.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Researchers can even compare current constructions of species interactions networks with historical reconstructions of ancient networks to determine how networks have changed over time.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Much research into these complex species interactions networks is highly concerned with understanding what factors (e.g., species richness, connectance, nature of the physical environment) lead to network stability.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Network analysis provides the ability to quantify associations between individuals, which makes it possible to infer details about the network as a whole at the species and/or population level.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] One of the most attractive features of the network paradigm would be that it provides a single conceptual framework in which the social organization of animals at all levels (individual, dyad, group, population) and for all types of interaction (aggressive, cooperative, sexual, etc.) can be studied.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Researchers interested in ethology across many taxa, from insects to primates, are starting to incorporate network analysis into their research.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Researchers interested in social insects (e.g., ants and bees) have used network analyses better to understand the division of labor, task allocation, and foraging optimization within colonies.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Other researchers are interested in how specific network properties at the group and/or population level can explain individual-level behaviors.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Studies have demonstrated how animal social network structure can be influenced by factors ranging from characteristics of the environment to characteristics of the individual, such as developmental experience and personality.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] At the level of the individual, the patterning of social connections can be an important determinant of fitness, predicting both survival and reproductive success.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] At the population level, network structure can influence the patterning of ecological and evolutionary processes, such as frequency-dependent selection and disease and information transmission.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] For instance, a study on wire-tailed manakins (a small passerine bird) found that a male's degree in the network largely predicted the ability of the male to rise in the social hierarchy (i.e., eventually obtain a territory and matings).
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Social network analysis can also be used to describe the social organization within a species more generally, which frequently reveals important proximate mechanisms promoting the use of certain behavioral strategies.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] These descriptions are frequently linked to ecological properties (e.g., resource distribution).
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Finally, social network analysis can also reveal important fluctuations in animal behaviors across changing environments.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Changes in an individual's social network environment can also influence characteristics such as 'personality': for example, social spiders that huddle with bolder neighbors tend to increase also in boldness.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] This is a very small set of broad examples of how researchers can use network analysis to study animal behavior.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Research in this area is currently expanding very rapidly, especially since the broader development of animal-borne tags and computer vision can be used to automate the collection of social associations.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Social network analysis is a valuable tool for studying animal behavior across all animal species and has the potential to uncover new information about animal behavior and social ecology that was previously poorly understood.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] To draw useful information from a biological network, an understanding of the statistical and mathematical techniques of identifying relationships within a network is vital.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Procedures to identify association, communities, and centrality within nodes in a biological network can provide insight into the relationships of whatever the nodes represent whether they are genes, species, etc.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Formulation of these methods transcends disciplines and relies heavily on graph theory, computer science, and bioinformatics.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] There are many different ways to measure the relationships of nodes when analyzing a network.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In many cases, the measure used to find nodes that share similarity within a network is specific to the application it is being used.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] One of the types of measures that biologists utilize is correlation which specifically centers around the linear relationship between two variables.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] As an example, weighted gene co-expression network analysis uses Pearson correlation to analyze linked gene expression and understand genetics at a systems level.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Another measure of correlation is linkage disequilibrium.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Linkage disequilibrium describes the non-random association of genetic sequences among loci in a given chromosome.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] An example of its use is in detecting relationships in GAM data across genomic intervals based upon detection frequencies of certain loci.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The concept of centrality can be extremely useful when analyzing biological network structures.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] There are many different methods to measure centrality such as degree, betweenness, closeness, Eigenvector, and Katz centrality.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Every type of centrality technique can provide different insights on nodes in a particular network; However, they all share the commonality that they are to measure the prominence of a node in a network.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In 2005, Researchers at Harvard Medical School utilized centrality measures with the yeast protein interaction network.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] They found that proteins that exhibited high Betweenness centrality were more essential and translated closely to a given protein's evolutionary age.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] These differing centrality measures reflect distinct structural roles of nodes within biological networks, including protein–protein interaction networks, gene regulatory networks, and metabolic networks.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] where *ki* is the number of nodes directly connected to node *i*, and *n* is the total number of nodes in the network.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In biological networks, nodes with high degree can be referred to as hubs and are associated with proteins or genes that participate in many interactions, contributing to core cellular functions.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] where *σst* is the total number of shortest paths between nodes *s* and *t*, and *σst(i)* is the number of those paths that pass through node *i*.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Nodes with high betweenness centrality can connect different regions of a network and facilitate interactions between them.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] where *d(i,j)* is the shortest path distance between nodes *i* and *j*, and *n* is the total number of nodes.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Nodes with high closeness centrality occupy central positions within the network and can interact with other nodes through relatively short paths, allowing efficient communication across the network.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] where *Aij* is the adjacency matrix (1 if nodes *i* and *j* are connected, 0 otherwise), *CE(j)* is the centrality of neighbor *j*, and *λ* is a constant (the largest eigenvalue of the adjacency matrix).
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In biological networks, this measure identifies nodes that are connected to other highly connected or influential nodes and is used to detect key regulators within complex systems.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] where *Aij* tells you if node *i* is connected to node *j* (1 = yes, 0 = no), *CK(j)* is the score of node *j*, *α* controls how much influence farther-away nodes have (smaller = less influence), and *β* gives every node a small base score.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] This measure accounts for the cumulative influence of a node across multiple steps in a network, which is relevant in multi-step biological processes.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] These centrality measures provide complementary approaches for analyzing the structure and organization of biological networks.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Studying the community structure of a network by subdividing groups of nodes into like-regions can be an integral tool for bioinformatics when exploring data as a network.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] A food web of The Secaucus High School Marsh exemplifies the benefits of grouping as the relationships between nodes are far easier to analyze with well-made communities.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] While the first graphic is hard to visualize, the second provides a better view of the pockets of highly connected feeding relationships that would be expected in a food web.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The problem of community detection is still an active problem.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Scientists and graph theorists continuously discover new ways of subsectioning networks and thus a plethora of different algorithms exist for creating these relationships.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Like many other tools that biologists utilize to understand data with network models, every algorithm can provide its own unique insight and may vary widely on aspects such as accuracy or time complexity of calculation.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] In 2002, a food web of marine mammals in the Chesapeake Bay was divided into communities by biologists using a community detection algorithm based on neighbors of nodes with high degree centrality.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The resulting communities displayed a sizable split in pelagic and benthic organisms.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Two very common community detection algorithms for biological networks are the Louvain Method and Leiden Algorithm.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The Louvain method is a greedy algorithm that attempts to maximize modularity, which favors heavy edges within communities and sparse edges between, within a set of nodes.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The algorithm starts by each node being in its own community and iteratively being added to the particular node's community that favors a higher modularity.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Once no modularity increase can occur by joining nodes to a community, a new weighted network is constructed of communities as nodes with edges representing between-community edges and loops representing edges within a community.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The process continues until no increase in modularity occurs.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] While the Louvain Method provides good community detection, there are a few ways that it is limited.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The Leiden Algorithm expands on the Louvain Method by providing a number of improvements.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] When joining nodes to a community, only neighborhoods that have been recently changed are considered.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] This greatly improves the speed of merging nodes.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Another optimization is in the refinement phase in which the algorithm randomly chooses for a node from a set of communities to merge with.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] This allows for greater depth in choosing communities as the Louvain Method solely focuses on maximizing the modularity that was chosen.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] The Leiden algorithm, while more complex than the Louvain Method, performs faster with better community detection and can be a valuable tool for identifying groups.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] Network motifs, or statistically significant recurring interaction patterns within a network, are a commonly used tool to understand biological networks.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] A major use case of network motifs is in Neurophysiology where motif analysis is commonly used to understand interconnected neuronal functions at varying scales.
[src:systems-biology/biological-network] As an example, in 2017, researchers at Beijing Normal University analyzed highly represented 2 and 3 node network motifs in directed functional brain networks constructed by Resting state fMRI data to study the basic mechanisms in brain information flow.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] A **Boolean network** consists of a discrete set of Boolean variables each of which has a Boolean function (possibly different for each variable) assigned to it which takes inputs from a subset of those variables and output that determines the state of the variable it is assigned to.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] This set of functions in effect determines a topology (connectivity) on the set of variables, which then become nodes in a network.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] Usually, the dynamics of the system is taken as a discrete time series where the state of the entire network at time *t*+1 is determined by evaluating each variable's function on the state of the network at time *t*.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] This may be done synchronously or asynchronously.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] Boolean networks have been used in biology to model regulatory networks.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] Although Boolean networks are a crude simplification of genetic reality where genes are not simple binary switches, there are several cases where they correctly convey the correct pattern of expressed and suppressed genes.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] The seemingly mathematical easy (synchronous) model was only fully understood in the mid 2000s.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] A Boolean network is a particular kind of sequential dynamical system, where time and states are discrete, i.e. both the set of variables and the set of states in the time series each have a bijection onto an integer series.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] A **random Boolean network** (RBN) is one that is randomly selected from the set of all possible Boolean networks of a particular size, *N*.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] One then can study statistically, how the expected properties of such networks depend on various statistical properties of the ensemble of all possible networks.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] For example, one may study how the RBN behavior changes as the average connectivity is changed.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] The first Boolean networks were proposed by Stuart A.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] Kauffman in 1969, as random models of genetic regulatory networks.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] If the attractor has only a single state it is called a *point attractor*, and if the attractor consists of more than one state it is called a *cycle attractor*.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] The set of states that lead to an attractor is called the *basin* of the attractor.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] States which occur only at the beginning of trajectories (no trajectories lead *to* them), are called *garden-of-Eden* states and the dynamics of the network flow from these states towards attractors.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] The time it takes to reach an attractor is called *transient time*.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] With growing computer power and increasing understanding of the seemingly simple model, different authors gave different estimates for the mean number and length of the attractors, here a brief summary of key publications.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] In dynamical systems theory, the structure and length of the attractors of a network corresponds to the dynamic phase of the network.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] The **stability of Boolean networks** depends on the connections of their nodes.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] A Boolean network can exhibit stable, critical or chaotic behavior.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] This phenomenon is governed by a critical value of the average number of connections of nodes ( $K_{c}$ ), and can be characterized by the Hamming distance as distance measure.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] In the unstable regime, the distance between two initially close states on average grows exponentially in time, while in the stable regime it decreases exponentially.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] In this, with "initially close states" one means that the Hamming distance is small compared with the number of nodes ( N ) in the network.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] For **N-K-model** the network is stable if $K<K_{c}$ , critical if $K=K_{c}$ , and unstable if $K>K_{c}$ .
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] The state of a given node $n_{i}$ is updated according to its truth table, whose outputs are randomly populated. $p_{i}$ denotes the probability of assigning an off output to a given series of input signals.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] If $p_{i}=p=const.$ for every node, the transition between the stable and chaotic range depends on p .
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] According to Bernard Derrida and Yves Pomeau , the critical value of the average number of connections is $K_{c}=1/[2p(1-p)]$ .
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] Sensitivity shows the probability that the output of the Boolean function of a given node changes if its input changes.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] In the general case, stability of the network is governed by the largest eigenvalue $\lambda _{Q}$ of matrix Q , where $Q_{ij}=q_{i}A_{ij}$ , and A is the adjacency matrix of the network.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] The network is stable if $\lambda _{Q}<1$ , critical if $\lambda _{Q}=1$ , unstable if $\lambda _{Q}>1$ .
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] One theme is to study **different underlying graph topologies**.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] Classical Boolean networks (sometimes called **CRBN**, i.e.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] Classic Random Boolean Network) are synchronously updated.
[src:systems-biology/boolean-network] Motivated by the fact that genes don't usually change their state simultaneously, different alternatives have been introduced.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In biochemistry and systems biology, **flux balance analysis** (**FBA**) is a mathematical method for simulating the metabolism of cells or entire unicellular organisms, such as *E. coli* or yeast, using genome-scale reconstructions of metabolic networks.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Genome-scale reconstructions describe all known or hypothesized biochemical reactions in an organism based on its entire genome.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] These reconstructions model metabolism by focusing on the interconversions between metabolites, identifying which metabolites are involved in the various reactions taking place in a cell or organism, and determining the genes that encode the enzymes which catalyze these reactions (if any).
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Earliest work in FBA dates back to the early 1980s.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Papoutsakis demonstrated that it was possible to construct flux balance equations using a metabolic map.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] It was Watson, however, who first introduced the idea of using linear programming and an objective function to solve for the fluxes in a pathway.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The first significant study was subsequently published by Fell and Small in 1986, who used flux balance analysis together with more elaborate objective functions to study the constraints in fat synthesis.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] FBA finds applications in bioprocess engineering to systematically identify modifications to the metabolic networks of microbes used in fermentation processes that improve product yields of industrially important chemicals such as ethanol and succinic acid.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] It has also been used for the identification of putative drug targets in cancer and pathogens, rational design of culture media, and host–pathogen interactions.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The results of FBA can be visualized for smaller networks using flux maps similar to the image on the right, which illustrates the steady-state fluxes carried by reactions in glycolysis.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The thickness of the arrows is proportional to the flux through the reaction.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In comparison to traditional methods of modeling, FBA is less intensive in terms of the input data required for constructing the model.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Simulations performed using FBA are computationally inexpensive and can calculate steady-state metabolic fluxes for large models (over 10,000 reactions) in a few seconds on modern personal computers.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This means that the effect of deleting reactions from the network and/or changing flux constraints can be sensibly modelled on a single computer.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] A frequently used technique to search a metabolic network for reactions that are particularly critical to the production of biomass.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Pairwise reaction deletion of all possible pairs of reactions is useful when looking for drug targets, as it allows the simulation of multi-target treatments, either by a single drug with multiple targets or by drug combinations.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Double deletion studies can also quantify the synthetic lethal interactions between different pathways providing a measure of the contribution of the pathway to overall network robustness.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Genes are connected to enzyme-catalyzed reactions by Boolean expressions known as Gene-Protein-Reaction expressions (GPR).
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Typically a GPR takes the form (Gene A AND Gene B) to indicate that the products of genes A and B are protein sub-units that assemble to form the complete protein and therefore the absence of either would result in deletion of the reaction.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] On the other hand, if the GPR is (Gene A OR Gene B) it implies that the products of genes A and B are isozymes, meaning that the expression of either one is sufficient to maintain an active reaction.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] A reaction can also be regulated by a single gene, or in the case of diffusion, it may not be associated with any gene at all.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Therefore, it is possible to evaluate the effect of single or multiple gene deletions by evaluation of the GPR as a Boolean expression.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] If the GPR evaluates to **false**, the reaction is constrained to zero in the model prior to performing FBA.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Thus gene knockouts can be simulated using FBA.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Logically, reactions that are not associated with any genes cannot be deleted.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The utility of reaction inhibition and deletion analyses becomes most apparent if a gene-protein-reaction matrix has been assembled for the network being studied with FBA.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The gene-protein-reaction matrix is a binary matrix connecting genes with the proteins made from them.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Using this matrix, reaction essentiality can be converted into gene essentiality indicating the gene defects which may cause a certain disease phenotype or the proteins/enzymes which are essential (and thus what enzymes are the most promising drug targets in pathogens).
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] However, the gene-protein-reaction matrix does not specify the Boolean relationship between genes with respect to the enzyme, instead it merely indicates an association between them.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Therefore, it should be used only if the Boolean GPR expression is unavailable.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The effect of inhibiting a reaction, rather than removing it entirely, can be simulated in FBA by restricting the allowed flux through it.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The effect of an inhibition can be classified as lethal or non-lethal by applying the same criteria as in the case of a deletion where a suitable threshold is used to distinguish "substantially reduced" from "slightly reduced".
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Generally the choice of threshold is arbitrary but a reasonable estimate can be obtained from growth experiments where the simulated inhibitions/deletions are actually performed and growth rate is measured.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] To design optimal growth media with respect to enhanced growth rates or useful by-product secretion, it is possible to use a method known as Phenotypic Phase Plane analysis.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] PhPP involves applying FBA repeatedly on the model while co-varying the nutrient uptake constraints and observing the value of the objective function (or by-product fluxes).
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] PhPP makes it possible to find the optimal combination of nutrients that favor a particular phenotype or a mode of metabolism resulting in higher growth rates or secretion of industrially useful by-products.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The predicted growth rates of bacteria in varying media have been shown to correlate well with experimental results, as well as to define precise minimal media for the culture of *Salmonella typhimurium*.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The human microbiota is a complex system with as many as 400 trillion microbes and bacteria interacting with each other and the host.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] To understand key factors in this system; a multi-scale, dynamic flux-balance analysis is proposed as FBA is classified as less computationally intensive.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] FBA formalizes the system of equations describing the concentration changes in a metabolic network as the dot product of a matrix of the stoichiometric coefficients (the stoichiometric matrix **S**) and the vector **v** of the unsolved fluxes.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The right-hand side of the dot product is a vector of zeros representing the system at steady state.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] At steady state, metabolite concentrations remain constant as the rates of production and consumption are balanced, resulting in no net change over time.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Since the system of equations is often underdetermined, there can be multiple possible solutions.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] To obtain a single solution, the flux that maximizes a reaction of interest, such as biomass or ATP production, is selected.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Linear programming is then used to calculate one of the possible solutions of fluxes corresponding to the steady state.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In contrast to the traditionally followed approach of metabolic modeling using coupled ordinary differential equations, flux balance analysis requires very little information in terms of the enzyme kinetic parameters and concentration of metabolites in the system.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] It achieves this by making two assumptions, steady state and optimality.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The first assumption is that the modeled system has entered a steady state, where the metabolite concentrations no longer change, i.e. in each metabolite node the producing and consuming fluxes cancel each other out.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The second assumption is that the organism has been optimized through evolution for some biological goal, such as optimal growth or conservation of resources.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The steady-state assumption dates to the ideas of material balance developed to model the growth of microbial cells in fermenters in bioprocess engineering.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] During microbial growth, a substrate consisting of a complex mixture of carbon, hydrogen, oxygen and nitrogen sources along with trace elements are consumed to generate biomass.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] If we consider the system of microbial cells to be at steady state then we may set the accumulation term to zero and reduce the material balance equations to simple algebraic equations.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In such a system, substrate becomes the input to the system which is consumed and biomass is produced becoming the output from the system.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Mathematically, the algebraic equations can be represented as a dot product of a matrix of coefficients and a vector of the unknowns.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Since the steady-state assumption puts the accumulation term to zero.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Extending this idea to metabolic networks, it is possible to represent a metabolic network as a stoichiometry balanced set of equations.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Moving to the matrix formalism, we can represent the equations as the dot product of a matrix of stoichiometry coefficients (stoichiometric matrix S ) and the vector of fluxes $\mathbf {v}$ as the unknowns and set the right hand side to 0 implying the steady state.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Metabolic networks typically have more reactions than metabolites and this gives an under-determined system of linear equations containing more variables than equations.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The standard approach to solve such under-determined systems is to apply linear programming.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] where **x** represents the vector of variables (to be determined), **c** and **b** are vectors of (known) coefficients, *A* is a (known) matrix of coefficients, and $(\cdot )^{\mathrm {T} }$ is the matrix transpose.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The expression to be maximized or minimized is called the *objective function* (**c**T**x** in this case).
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The inequalities *A***x** ≤ **b** are the constraints which specify a convex polytope over which the objective function is to be optimized.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Linear Programming requires the definition of an objective function.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The optimal solution to the LP problem is considered to be the solution which maximizes or minimizes the value of the objective function depending on the case in point.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In the case of flux balance analysis, the objective function **Z** for the LP is often defined as biomass production.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Biomass production is simulated by an equation representing a lumped reaction that converts various biomass precursors into one unit of biomass.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] where $\mathbf {v}$ represents the vector of fluxes (to be determined), S is a (known) matrix of coefficients.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The expression to be maximized or minimized is called the *objective function* ( $\mathbf {c} ^{\mathrm {T} }\mathbf {v}$ in this case).
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The inequalities $\mathbf {lowerbound} \leq \mathbf {v}$ and $\mathbf {v} \leq \mathbf {upperbound}$ define, respectively, the minimal and the maximal rates of flux for every reaction corresponding to the columns of the S matrix.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] These rates can be experimentally determined to constrain and improve the predictive accuracy of the model even further or they can be specified to an arbitrarily high value indicating no constraint on the flux through the reaction.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The stoichiometric coefficients alone are sufficient for the mathematical maximization of a specific objective function.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The objective function is essentially a measure of how each component in the system contributes to the production of the desired product.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The product itself depends on the purpose of the model, but one of the most common examples is the study of total biomass.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] A notable example of the success of FBA is the ability to accurately predict the growth rate of the prokaryote *E. coli* when cultured in different conditions.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In this case, the metabolic system was optimized to maximize the biomass objective function.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] However this model can be used to optimize the production of any product, and is often used to determine the output level of some biotechnologically relevant product.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The model itself can be experimentally verified by cultivating organisms using a chemostat or similar tools to ensure that nutrient concentrations are held constant.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Measurements of the production of the desired objective can then be used to correct the model.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The key parts of model preparation are: creating a metabolic network without gaps, adding constraints to the model, and finally adding an objective function (often called the Biomass function), usually to simulate the growth of the organism being modelled.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Metabolic networks can vary in scope from those describing a single pathway to those describing cell, tissue, or organism.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The main requirement of a metabolic network that forms the basis of an FBA-ready network is that it contains no gaps and correctly accounts for mass and charge balances of all biochemical processes therein.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This typically means that extensive manual curation is required, making the preparation of a metabolic network for flux-balance analysis a process that can take months or years.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] However, recent advances, such as so-called gap-filling or mass-and-charge correction methods, can reduce the required time to weeks or months.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Software packages for creation of FBA models include: Pathway Tools/MetaFlux, Simpheny, MetNetMaker, COBRApy, CarveMe, MIOM, or COBREXA.jl.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Generally models are created in BioPAX, SBML, or Json format so that further analysis or visualization can take place in other software although this is not a requirement.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] A key part of FBA is the ability to add constraints to the flux rates of reactions within networks, forcing them to stay within a range of selected values.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This lets the model more accurately simulate real metabolism.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The constraints belong to two subsets from a biological perspective; boundary constraints that limit nutrient uptake/excretion and internal constraints that limit the flux through reactions within the organism.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In mathematical terms, the application of constraints can be considered to reduce the solution space of the FBA model.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In addition to constraints applied at the edges of a metabolic network, constraints can be applied to reactions deep within the network.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] These constraints are usually simple; they may constrain the direction of a reaction due to energy considerations or constrain the maximum speed of a reaction due to the finite speed of all reactions in nature.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Organisms, and all other metabolic systems, require some input of nutrients.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] If the rate of absorption (and/or excretion) of certain nutrients can be experimentally measured then this information can be added as a constraint on the flux rate at the edges of a metabolic model.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This ensures that nutrients that are not present or not absorbed by the organism do not enter its metabolism (the flux rate is constrained to zero) and also means that known nutrient uptake rates are adhered to by the simulation.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This provides a secondary method of making sure that the simulated metabolism has experimentally verified properties rather than just mathematically acceptable ones.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In principle, all reactions are reversible however in practice reactions often effectively occur in only one direction.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This may be due to significantly higher concentration of reactants compared to the concentration of the products of the reaction.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] But more often it happens because the products of a reaction have a much lower free energy than the reactants and therefore the forward direction of a reaction is favored more.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Certain flux rates can be measured experimentally ( $v_{i,m}\,$ ) and the fluxes within a metabolic model can be constrained, within some error ( $\varepsilon \,$ ), to ensure these known flux rates are accurately reproduced in the simulation.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Flux rates are most easily measured for nutrient uptake at the edge of the network.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Measurements of internal fluxes is possible using radioactively labelled or NMR visible metabolites.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Constrained FBA-ready metabolic models can be analyzed using software such as the COBRA toolbox (available implementations in MATLAB and Python), SurreyFBA, or the web-based FAME.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Additional software packages have been listed elsewhere.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] A comprehensive review of all such software and their functionalities has been recently reviewed.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] An open-source alternative is available in the R (programming language) as the packages abcdeFBA or sybil for performing FBA and other constraint based modeling techniques.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] FBA can give a large number of mathematically acceptable solutions to the steady-state problem $(S{\vec {v}}=0)$ .
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] However solutions of biological interest are the ones which produce the desired metabolites in the correct proportion.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The objective function defines the proportion of these metabolites.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] For instance when modelling the growth of an organism the objective function is generally defined as biomass.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Mathematically, it is a column in the stoichiometry matrix the entries of which place a "demand" or act as a "sink" for biosynthetic precursors such as fatty acids, amino acids and cell wall components which are present on the corresponding rows of the **S** matrix.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] These entries represent experimentally measured, dry weight proportions of cellular components.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Therefore, this column becomes a lumped reaction that simulates growth and reproduction.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Therefore, the accuracy of experimental measurements plays an essential role in the correct definition of the biomass function and makes the results of FBA biologically applicable by ensuring that the correct proportion of metabolites are produced by metabolism.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] When modeling smaller networks the objective function can be changed accordingly.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] An example of this would be in the study of the carbohydrate metabolism pathways where the objective function would probably be defined as a certain proportion of ATP and NADH and thus simulate the production of high energy metabolites by this pathway.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Linear programming can be used to find a single optimal solution.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In the more general case any reaction can be defined and added to the biomass function with either the condition that it be maximised or minimised if a single "optimal" solution is desired.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In the case of there being only a single separate biomass function/reaction within the stoichiometric matrix ${\vec {c}}$ would simplify to all zeroes with a value of 1 (or any non-zero value) in the position corresponding to that biomass function.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Where there were multiple separate objective functions ${\vec {c}}$ would simplify to all zeroes with weighted values in the positions corresponding to all objective functions.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The analysis of the null space of matrices is implemented in software packages specialized for matrix operations such as Matlab and Octave.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Determination of the null space of $\scriptstyle \mathbf {S}$ tells us all the possible collections of flux vectors (or linear combinations thereof) that balance fluxes within the biological network.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The advantage of this approach becomes evident in biological systems which are described by differential equation systems with many unknowns.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The velocities in the differential equations above — $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$ — are dependent on the reaction rates of the underlying equations.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The velocities are generally taken from the Michaelis–Menten kinetic theory, which involves the kinetic parameters of the enzymes catalyzing the reactions and the concentration of the metabolites themselves.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Isolating enzymes from living organisms and measuring their kinetic parameters is a difficult task, as is measuring the internal concentrations and diffusion constants of metabolites within an organism.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Therefore, the differential equation approach to metabolic modeling is beyond the current scope of science for all but the most studied organisms.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] FBA avoids this impediment by applying the homeostatic assumption, which is a reasonably approximate description of biological systems.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Although FBA avoids that biological obstacle, the mathematical issue of a large solution space remains.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Accurately representing the biological limits of the system and returning the flux distribution closest to the natural fluxes within the target system/organism.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Certain biological principles can help overcome the mathematical difficulties.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The success of FBA and the realization of its limitations has led to extensions that attempt to mediate the limitations of the technique.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The optimal solution to the flux-balance problem is rarely unique with many possible, and equally optimal, solutions existing.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Flux variability analysis (FVA), built into some analysis software, returns the boundaries for the fluxes through each reaction that can, paired with the right combination of other fluxes, estimate the optimal solution.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Reactions which can support a low variability of fluxes through them are likely to be of a higher importance to an organism and FVA is a promising technique for the identification of reactions that are important.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] When simulating knockouts or growth on media, FBA gives the final steady-state flux distribution.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This final steady state is reached in varying time-scales.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] For example, the predicted growth rate of *E. coli* on glycerol as the primary carbon source did not match the FBA predictions; however, on sub-culturing for 40 days or 700 generations, the growth rate adaptively evolved to match the FBA prediction.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Sometimes it is of interest to find out what is the immediate effect of a perturbation or knockout, since it takes time for regulatory changes to occur and for the organism to re-organize fluxes to optimally utilize a different carbon source or circumvent the effect of the knockout.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] MOMA predicts the immediate sub-optimal flux distribution following the perturbation by minimizing the distance (Euclidean) between the wild-type FBA flux distribution and the mutant flux distribution using quadratic programming.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This yields an optimization problem of the form.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] where $\mathbf {v_{w}}$ represents the wild-type (or unperturbed state) flux distribution and $\mathbf {v_{d}}$ represents the flux distribution on gene deletion that is to be solved for.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This is the MOMA solution which represents the flux distribution immediately post-perturbation.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] ROOM attempts to improve the prediction of the metabolic state of an organism after a gene knockout.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] It follows the same premise as MOMA that an organism would try to restore a flux distribution as close as possible to the wild-type after a knockout.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] However it further hypothesizes that this steady state would be reached through a series of transient metabolic changes by the regulatory network and that the organism would try to minimize the number of regulatory changes required to reach the wild-type state.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Instead of using a distance metric minimization however it uses a mixed integer linear programming method.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Dynamic FBA attempts to add the ability for models to change over time, thus in some ways avoiding the strict steady state condition of pure FBA.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Typically the technique involves running an FBA simulation, changing the model based on the outputs of that simulation, and rerunning the simulation.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] By repeating this process an element of feedback is achieved over time.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] FBA provides a less simplistic analysis than choke point analysis while requiring far less information on reaction rates and a much less complete network reconstruction than a full dynamic simulation would require.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] In filling this niche, FBA has been shown to be a very useful technique for analysis of the metabolic capabilities of cellular systems.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This means that network effects, such as chemical reactions in distant pathways affecting each other, can be reproduced in the model.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] The upside to the inability of choke point analysis to simulate network effects is that it considers each reaction within a network in isolation and thus can suggest important reactions in a network even if a network is highly fragmented and contains many gaps.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Unlike dynamic metabolic simulation, FBA assumes that the internal concentration of metabolites within a system stays constant over time and thus is unable to provide anything other than steady-state solutions.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] It is unlikely that FBA could, for example, simulate the functioning of a nerve cell.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] Since the internal concentration of metabolites is not considered within a model, it is possible that an FBA solution could contain metabolites at a concentration too high to be biologically acceptable.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] This is a problem that dynamic metabolic simulations would probably avoid.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] One advantage of the simplicity of FBA over dynamic simulations is that they are far less computationally expensive, allowing the simulation of large numbers of perturbations to the network.
[src:systems-biology/flux-balance-analysis] A second advantage is that the reconstructed model can be substantially simpler by avoiding the need to consider enzyme rates and the effect of complex interactions on enzyme kinetics.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] A **gene** (or **genetic**) **regulatory network** (**GRN**) is a collection of molecular regulators that interact with each other and with other substances in the cell to govern the gene expression levels of mRNA and proteins which, in turn, determine the function of the cell.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] GRNs also play a central role in morphogenesis, the creation of body structures, which is central to evolutionary developmental biology (evo-devo).
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The regulator can be DNA, RNA, protein or any combination of two or more of these three that form a complex, such as a specific sequence of DNA and a transcription factor to activate that sequence.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The interaction can be direct or indirect (through transcribed RNA or translated protein).
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In general, each mRNA molecule goes on to make a specific protein (or set of proteins).
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In some cases this protein will be structural, and will accumulate at the cell membrane or within the cell to give it particular structural properties.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In other cases the protein will be an enzyme, i.e., a micro-machine that catalyses a certain reaction, such as the breakdown of a food source or toxin.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Some proteins serve only to activate other genes, though, and these are the transcription factors that are the main actors in regulatory networks or cascades.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] By binding to the promoter region at the start of other genes they turn them on, initiating the production of another protein, and so on.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Some transcription factors are inhibitory.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In single-celled organisms, regulatory networks respond to the external environment, optimising the cell at a given time for survival in this environment.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Thus a yeast cell in a sugar solution will turn on genes to make enzymes that process the sugar to alcohol.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] This process, which we associate with wine-making, is how the yeast cell makes its living, gaining energy to multiply, which under normal circumstances would enhance its survival prospects.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In multicellular animals the same principle has been put in the service of gene cascades that control body-shape.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Each time a cell divides, two cells result which, although they contain the same genome in full, can differ in which genes are turned on and making proteins.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Sometimes a 'self-sustaining feedback loop' ensures that a cell maintains its identity and passes it on.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Less understood is the mechanism of epigenetics by which chromatin modification may provide cellular memory by blocking or allowing transcription.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] A major feature of multicellular animals is the use of morphogen gradients, which in effect provide a positioning system that tells a cell where in the body it is, and hence what sort of cell to become.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] A gene that is turned on in one cell may make a product that leaves the cell and diffuses through adjacent cells, entering them and turning on genes only when it is present above a certain threshold level.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] These cells are thus induced into a new fate, and may even generate other morphogens that signal back to the original cell.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Over longer distances morphogens may use the active process of signal transduction.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Such signalling controls embryogenesis, the building of a body plan from scratch through a series of sequential steps.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] They also control and maintain adult bodies through feedback processes, and the loss of such feedback because of a mutation can be responsible for the cell proliferation that is seen in cancer.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In parallel with this process of building structure, the gene cascade turns on genes that make structural proteins that give each cell the physical properties it needs.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] At one level, biological cells can be thought of as "partially mixed bags" of biological chemicals – in the discussion of gene regulatory networks, these chemicals are mostly the messenger RNAs (mRNAs) and proteins that arise from gene expression.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] These mRNA and proteins interact with each other with various degrees of specificity.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Others are bound to cell membranes, interacting with molecules in the environment.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Still others pass through cell membranes and mediate long range signals to other cells in a multi-cellular organism.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] These molecules and their interactions comprise a *gene regulatory network*.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The nodes of this network can represent genes, proteins, mRNAs, protein/protein complexes or cellular processes.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Nodes that are depicted as lying along vertical lines are associated with the cell/environment interfaces, while the others are free-floating and can diffuse.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The nodes can regulate themselves directly or indirectly, creating feedback loops, which form cyclic chains of dependencies in the topological network.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The network structure is an abstraction of the system's molecular or chemical dynamics, describing the manifold ways in which one substance affects all the others to which it is connected.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In practice, such GRNs are inferred from the biological literature on a given system and represent a distillation of the collective knowledge about a set of related biochemical reactions.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] To speed up the manual curation of GRNs, some recent efforts try to use text mining, curated databases, network inference from massive data, model checking and other information extraction technologies for this purpose.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Genes can be viewed as nodes in the network, with input being proteins such as transcription factors, and outputs being the level of gene expression.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The value of the node depends on a function which depends on the value of its regulators in previous time steps (in the Boolean network described below these are Boolean functions, typically AND, OR, and NOT).
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] These functions have been interpreted as performing a kind of information processing within the cell, which determines cellular behavior.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The basic drivers within cells are concentrations of some proteins, which determine both spatial (location within the cell or tissue) and temporal (cell cycle or developmental stage) coordinates of the cell, as a kind of "cellular memory".
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The gene networks are only beginning to be understood, and it is a next step for biology to attempt to deduce the functions for each gene "node", to help understand the behavior of the system in increasing levels of complexity, from gene to signaling pathway, cell or tissue level.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Mathematical models of GRNs have been developed to capture the behavior of the system being modeled, and in some cases generate predictions corresponding with experimental observations.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In some other cases, models have proven to make accurate novel predictions, which can be tested experimentally, thus suggesting new approaches to explore in an experiment that sometimes wouldn't be considered in the design of the protocol of an experimental laboratory.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Modeling techniques include differential equations (ODEs), Boolean networks, Petri nets, Bayesian networks, graphical Gaussian network models, Stochastic, and Process Calculi.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Conversely, techniques have been proposed for generating models of GRNs that best explain a set of time series observations.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Recently it has been shown that ChIP-seq signal of histone modification are more correlated with transcription factor motifs at promoters in comparison to RNA level.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Hence it is proposed that time-series histone modification ChIP-seq could provide more reliable inference of gene-regulatory networks in comparison to methods based on expression levels.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Gene regulatory networks are generally thought to be made up of a few highly connected nodes (hubs) and many poorly connected nodes nested within a hierarchical regulatory regime.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Thus gene regulatory networks approximate a hierarchical scale free network topology.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] This is consistent with the view that most genes have limited pleiotropy and operate within regulatory modules.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] This structure is thought to evolve due to the preferential attachment of duplicated genes to more highly connected genes.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Recent work has also shown that natural selection tends to favor networks with sparse connectivity.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] There are primarily two ways that networks can evolve, both of which can occur simultaneously.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The first is that network topology can be changed by the addition or subtraction of nodes (genes) or parts of the network (modules) may be expressed in different contexts.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The*Drosophila* Hippo signaling pathway provides a good example.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The Hippo signaling pathway controls both mitotic growth and post-mitotic cellular differentiation.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Recently it was found that the network the Hippo signaling pathway operates in differs between these two functions which in turn changes the behavior of the Hippo signaling pathway.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] This suggests that the Hippo signaling pathway operates as a conserved regulatory module that can be used for multiple functions depending on context.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Thus, changing network topology can allow a conserved module to serve multiple functions and alter the final output of the network.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The second way networks can evolve is by changing the strength of interactions between nodes, such as how strongly a transcription factor may bind to a cis-regulatory element.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Such variation in strength of network edges has been shown to underlie between species variation in vulva cell fate patterning of *Caenorhabditis* worms.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Another characteristic of gene regulatory network is their abundance of certain repetitive sub-networks known as network motifs.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Network motifs can be regarded as repetitive topological patterns when dividing a big network into small blocks.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Several types of motifs appear more often in gene regulatory networks than in randomly generated networks.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] As an example, one such motif is called feed-forward loops, which consist of three nodes.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] This motif is the most abundant among all possible motifs made up of three nodes, as is shown in the gene regulatory networks of fly, nematode, and human.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The enriched motifs have been proposed to follow convergent evolution, suggesting they are "optimal designs" for certain regulatory purposes.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] For example, modeling shows that feed-forward loops are able to coordinate the change in node A (in terms of concentration and activity) and the expression dynamics of node C, creating different input-output behaviors.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The galactose utilization system of *E. coli* contains a feed-forward loop which accelerates the activation of galactose utilization operon *galETK*, potentially facilitating the metabolic transition to galactose when glucose is depleted.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The feed-forward loop in the arabinose utilization systems of *E.coli* delays the activation of arabinose catabolism operon and transporters, potentially avoiding unnecessary metabolic transition due to temporary fluctuations in upstream signaling pathways.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Similarly in the Wnt signaling pathway of *Xenopus*, the feed-forward loop acts as a fold-change detector that responses to the fold change, rather than the absolute change, in the level of β-catenin, potentially increasing the resistance to fluctuations in β-catenin levels.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Following the convergent evolution hypothesis, the enrichment of feed-forward loops would be an adaptation for fast response and noise resistance.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] A recent research found that yeast grown in an environment of constant glucose developed mutations in glucose signaling pathways and growth regulation pathway, suggesting regulatory components responding to environmental changes are dispensable under constant environment.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] On the other hand, some researchers hypothesize that the enrichment of network motifs is non-adaptive.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In other words, gene regulatory networks can evolve to a similar structure without the specific selection on the proposed input-output behavior.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Support for this hypothesis often comes from computational simulations.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] For example, fluctuations in the abundance of feed-forward loops in a model that simulates the evolution of gene regulatory networks by randomly rewiring nodes may suggest that the enrichment of feed-forward loops is a side-effect of evolution.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In another model of gene regulator networks evolution, the ratio of the frequencies of gene duplication and gene deletion show great influence on network topology: certain ratios lead to the enrichment of feed-forward loops and create networks that show features of hierarchical scale free networks.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] A heuristic approach to developing GRNs has the potential to improve understanding of gene regulation by modelling GRNs as small-world networks, in which genes are densely interconnected through a small number of intermediate regulatory steps, enabling rapid signal propagation across the network.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] This reveals that GRNs exhibit scale-free topology, characterised by a small number of highly connected hub genes that exert disproportionate regulatory influence over the broader network.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Regulatory networks allow bacteria to adapt to almost every environmental niche on earth.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] A network of interactions among diverse types of molecules including DNA, RNA, proteins and metabolites, is utilised by the bacteria to achieve regulation of gene expression.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In bacteria, the principal function of regulatory networks is to control the response to environmental changes, for example nutritional status and environmental stress.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] A complex organization of networks permits the microorganism to coordinate and integrate multiple environmental signals.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] One example stress is when the environment suddenly becomes poor of nutrients.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] This triggers a complex adaptation process in bacteria, such as *E. coli.* After this environmental change, thousands of genes change expression level.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] However, these changes are predictable from the topology and logic of the gene network that is reported in RegulonDB.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Specifically, on average, the response strength of a gene was predictable from the difference between the numbers of activating and repressing input transcription factors of that gene.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] It is common to model such a network with a set of coupled ordinary differential equations (ODEs) or SDEs, describing the reaction kinetics of the constituent parts.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Suppose that our regulatory network has N nodes, and let $S_{1}(t),S_{2}(t),\ldots ,S_{N}(t)$ represent the concentrations of the N corresponding substances at time t .
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] where the functions $f_{j}$ express the dependence of $S_{j}$ on the concentrations of other substances present in the cell.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The functions $f_{j}$ are ultimately derived from basic principles of chemical kinetics or simple expressions derived from these e.g.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Hence, the functional forms of the $f_{j}$ are usually chosen as low-order polynomials or Hill functions that serve as an ansatz for the real molecular dynamics.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Such models are then studied using the mathematics of nonlinear dynamics.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] System-specific information, like reaction rate constants and sensitivities, are encoded as constant parameters.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] for all j , one obtains (possibly several) concentration profiles of proteins and mRNAs that are theoretically sustainable (though not necessarily stable).
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Steady states of kinetic equations thus correspond to potential cell types, and oscillatory solutions to the above equation to naturally cyclic cell types.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Mathematical stability of these attractors can usually be characterized by the sign of higher derivatives at critical points, and then correspond to biochemical stability of the concentration profile.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Critical points and bifurcations in the equations correspond to critical cell states in which small state or parameter perturbations could switch the system between one of several stable differentiation fates.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Trajectories correspond to the unfolding of biological pathways and transients of the equations to short-term biological events.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] For a more mathematical discussion, see the articles on nonlinearity, dynamical systems, bifurcation theory, and chaos theory.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The following example illustrates how a Boolean network can model a GRN together with its gene products (the outputs) and the substances from the environment that affect it (the inputs).
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Stuart Kauffman was amongst the first biologists to use the metaphor of Boolean networks to model genetic regulatory networks.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Each node in the graph can be in one of two states: on or off.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] For a gene, "on" corresponds to the gene being expressed; for inputs and outputs, "on" corresponds to the substance being present.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Time is viewed as proceeding in discrete steps.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] At each step, the new state of a node is a Boolean function of the prior states of the nodes with arrows pointing towards it.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The validity of the model can be tested by comparing simulation results with time series observations.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] A partial validation of a Boolean network model can also come from testing the predicted existence of a yet unknown regulatory connection between two particular transcription factors that each are nodes of the model.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Continuous network models of GRNs are an extension of the Boolean networks described above.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Nodes still represent genes and connections between them regulatory influences on gene expression.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Genes in biological systems display a continuous range of activity levels and it has been argued that using a continuous representation captures several properties of gene regulatory networks not present in the Boolean model.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Formally most of these approaches are similar to an artificial neural network, as inputs to a node are summed up and the result serves as input to a sigmoid function, e.g., but proteins do often control gene expression in a synergistic, i.e. non-linear, way.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] However, there is now a continuous network model that allows grouping of inputs to a node thus realizing another level of regulation.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] This model is formally closer to a higher order recurrent neural network.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The same model has also been used to mimic the evolution of cellular differentiation and even multicellular morphogenesis.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Experimental results have demonstrated that gene expression is a stochastic process.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Thus, many authors are now using the stochastic formalism, after the work by Arkin et al.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Works on single gene expression and small synthetic genetic networks, such as the genetic toggle switch of Tim Gardner and Jim Collins, provided additional experimental data on the phenotypic variability and the stochastic nature of gene expression.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The first versions of stochastic models of gene expression involved only instantaneous reactions and were driven by the Gillespie algorithm.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] From here, a set of reactions was proposed that allow generating GRNs.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] These are then simulated using a modified version of the Gillespie algorithm, that can simulate multiple time delayed reactions (chemical reactions where each of the products is provided a time delay that determines when will it be released in the system as a "finished product").
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Furthermore, there seems to be a trade-off between the noise in gene expression, the speed with which genes can switch, and the metabolic cost associated their functioning.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] More specifically, for any given level of metabolic cost, there is an optimal trade-off between noise and processing speed and increasing the metabolic cost leads to better speed-noise trade-offs.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] A recent work proposed a simulator (SGNSim, *Stochastic Gene Networks Simulator*), that can model GRNs where transcription and translation are modeled as multiple time delayed events and its dynamics is driven by a stochastic simulation algorithm (SSA) able to deal with multiple time delayed events.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The time delays can be drawn from several distributions and the reaction rates from complex functions or from physical parameters.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] SGNSim can generate ensembles of GRNs within a set of user-defined parameters, such as topology.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] It can also be used to model specific GRNs and systems of chemical reactions.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Genetic perturbations such as gene deletions, gene over-expression, insertions, frame shift mutations can also be modeled as well.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The GRN is created from a graph with the desired topology, imposing in-degree and out-degree distributions.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Gene promoter activities are affected by other genes expression products that act as inputs, in the form of monomers or combined into multimers and set as direct or indirect.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Next, each direct input is assigned to an operator site and different transcription factors can be allowed, or not, to compete for the same operator site, while indirect inputs are given a target.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Finally, a function is assigned to each gene, defining the gene's response to a combination of transcription factors (promoter state).
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The transfer functions (that is, how genes respond to a combination of inputs) can be assigned to each combination of promoter states as desired.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] In other recent work, multiscale models of gene regulatory networks have been developed that focus on synthetic biology applications.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Simulations have been used that model all biomolecular interactions in transcription, translation, regulation, and induction of gene regulatory networks, guiding the design of synthetic systems.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Other work has focused on predicting the gene expression levels in a gene regulatory network.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] The approaches used to model gene regulatory networks have been constrained to be interpretable and, as a result, are generally simplified versions of the network.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] For example, Boolean networks have been used due to their simplicity and ability to handle noisy data but lose data information by having a binary representation of the genes.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Also, artificial neural networks omit using a hidden layer so that they can be interpreted, losing the ability to model higher order correlations in the data.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Using a model that is not constrained to be interpretable, a more accurate model can be produced.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Being able to predict gene expressions more accurately provides a way to explore how drugs affect a system of genes as well as for finding which genes are interrelated in a process.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] This has been encouraged by the DREAM competition which promotes a competition for the best prediction algorithms.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Some other recent work has used artificial neural networks with a hidden layer.
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] There are three classes of multiple sclerosis: relapsing-remitting (RRMS), primary progressive (PPMS) and secondary progressive (SPMS).
[src:systems-biology/gene-regulatory-network] Gene regulatory network (GRN) plays a vital role to understand the disease mechanism across these three different multiple sclerosis classes.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The related method of flux balance analysis seeks to mathematically simulate metabolism in genome-scale reconstructions of metabolic networks.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] A metabolic reconstruction provides a highly mathematical, structured platform on which to understand the systems biology of metabolic pathways within an organism.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The integration of biochemical metabolic pathways with rapidly available, annotated genome sequences has developed what are called genome-scale metabolic models.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Simply put, these models correlate metabolic genes with metabolic pathways.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] In general, the more information about physiology, biochemistry and genetics is available for the target organism, the better the predictive capacity of the reconstructed models.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Mechanically speaking, the process of reconstructing prokaryotic and eukaryotic metabolic networks is essentially the same.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Having said this, eukaryote reconstructions are typically more challenging because of the size of genomes, coverage of knowledge, and the multitude of cellular compartments.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The first genome-scale metabolic model was generated in 1995 for *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The first multicellular organism, *C. elegans*, was reconstructed in 1998.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Since then, many reconstructions have been formed.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] For a list of reconstructions that have been converted into a model and experimentally validated, see http://sbrg.ucsd.edu/InSilicoOrganisms/OtherOrganisms.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Because the timescale for the development of reconstructions is so recent, most reconstructions have been built manually.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] However, now, there are quite a few resources that allow for the semi-automatic assembly of these reconstructions that are utilized due to the time and effort necessary for a reconstruction.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] An initial fast reconstruction can be developed automatically using resources like PathoLogic or ERGO in combination with encyclopedias like MetaCyc, and then manually updated by using resources like PathwayTools.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] These semi-automatic methods allow for a fast draft to be created while allowing the fine tune adjustments required once new experimental data is found.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] It is only in this manner that the field of metabolic reconstructions will keep up with the ever-increasing numbers of annotated genomes.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] A reconstruction is built by compiling data from the resources above.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Database tools such as KEGG and BioCyc can be used in conjunction with each other to find all the metabolic genes in the organism of interest.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] These genes will be compared to closely related organisms that have already developed reconstructions to find homologous genes and reactions.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] These homologous genes and reactions are carried over from the known reconstructions to form the draft reconstruction of the organism of interest.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Tools such as ERGO, Pathway Tools and Model SEED can compile data into pathways to form a network of metabolic and non-metabolic pathways.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] These networks are then verified and refined before being made into a mathematical simulation.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The predictive aspect of a metabolic reconstruction hinges on the ability to predict the biochemical reaction catalyzed by a protein using that protein's amino acid sequence as an input, and to infer the structure of a metabolic network based on the predicted set of reactions.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] A network of enzymes and metabolites is drafted to relate sequences and function.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] When an uncharacterized protein is found in the genome, its amino acid sequence is first compared to those of previously characterized proteins to search for homology.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] When a homologous protein is found, the proteins are considered to have a common ancestor and their functions are inferred as being similar.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] However, the quality of a reconstruction model is dependent on its ability to accurately infer phenotype directly from sequence, so this rough estimation of protein function will not be sufficient.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Once proteins have been established, more information about the enzyme structure, reactions catalyzed, substrates and products, mechanisms, and more can be acquired from databases such as KEGG, MetaCyc and NC-IUBMB.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Accurate metabolic reconstructions require additional information about the reversibility and preferred physiological direction of an enzyme-catalyzed reaction which can come from databases such as BRENDA or MetaCyc database.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] An initial metabolic reconstruction of a genome is typically far from perfect due to the high variability and diversity of microorganisms.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Often, metabolic pathway databases such as KEGG and MetaCyc will have "holes", meaning that there is a conversion from a substrate to a product (i.e., an enzymatic activity) for which there is no known protein in the genome that encodes the enzyme that facilitates the catalysis.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] What can also happen in semi-automatically drafted reconstructions is that some pathways are falsely predicted and don't actually occur in the predicted manner.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Because of this, a systematic verification is made in order to make sure no inconsistencies are present and that all the entries listed are correct and accurate.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Furthermore, previous literature can be researched in order to support any information obtained from one of the many metabolic reaction and genome databases.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] This provides an added level of assurance for the reconstruction that the enzyme and the reaction it catalyzes do actually occur in the organism.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Enzyme promiscuity and spontaneous chemical reactions can damage metabolites.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] This metabolite damage, and its repair or pre-emption, create energy costs that need to be incorporated into models.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] It is likely that many genes of unknown function encode proteins that repair or pre-empt metabolite damage, but most genome-scale metabolic reconstructions only include a fraction of all genes.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Any new reaction not present in the databases needs to be added to the reconstruction.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] This is an iterative process that cycles between the experimental phase and the coding phase.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] As new information is found about the target organism, the model will be adjusted to predict the metabolic and phenotypical output of the cell.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The presence or absence of certain reactions of the metabolism will affect the amount of reactants/products that are present for other reactions within the particular pathway.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] This is because products in one reaction go on to become the reactants for another reaction, i.e. products of one reaction can combine with other proteins or compounds to form new proteins/compounds in the presence of different enzymes or catalysts.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Francke *et al.* provide an excellent example as to why the verification step of the project needs to be performed in significant detail.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] During a metabolic network reconstruction of *Lactobacillus plantarum*, the model showed that succinyl-CoA was one of the reactants for a reaction that was a part of the biosynthesis of methionine.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] However, an understanding of the physiology of the organism would have revealed that due to an incomplete tricarboxylic acid pathway, *Lactobacillus plantarum* does not actually produce succinyl-CoA, and the correct reactant for that part of the reaction was acetyl-CoA.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Therefore, systematic verification of the initial reconstruction will bring to light several inconsistencies that can adversely affect the final interpretation of the reconstruction, which is to accurately comprehend the molecular mechanisms of the organism.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Furthermore, the simulation step also ensures that all the reactions present in the reconstruction are properly balanced.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] To sum up, a reconstruction that is fully accurate can lead to greater insight about understanding the functioning of the organism of interest.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] A metabolic network can be broken down into a stoichiometric matrix where the rows represent the compounds of the reactions, while the columns of the matrix correspond to the reactions themselves.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Stoichiometry is a quantitative relationship between substrates of a chemical reaction.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] In order to deduce what the metabolic network suggests, recent research has centered on a few approaches, such as extreme pathways, elementary mode analysis, flux balance analysis, and a number of other constraint-based modeling methods.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Price, Reed, and Papin, from the Palsson lab, use a method of singular value decomposition (SVD) of extreme pathways in order to understand regulation of a human red blood cell metabolism.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Extreme pathways are convex basis vectors that consist of steady state functions of a metabolic network.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] For any particular metabolic network, there is always a unique set of extreme pathways available.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Furthermore, Price, Reed, and Papin, define a constraint-based approach, where through the help of constraints like mass balance and maximum reaction rates, it is possible to develop a 'solution space' where all the feasible options fall within.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Then, using a kinetic model approach, a single solution that falls within the extreme pathway solution space can be determined.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Therefore, in their study, Price, Reed, and Papin, use both constraint and kinetic approaches to understand the human red blood cell metabolism.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] In conclusion, using extreme pathways, the regulatory mechanisms of a metabolic network can be studied in further detail.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Elementary mode analysis closely matches the approach used by extreme pathways.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Similar to extreme pathways, there is always a unique set of elementary modes available for a particular metabolic network.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] These are the smallest sub-networks that allow a metabolic reconstruction network to function in steady state.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] According to Stelling (2002), elementary modes can be used to understand cellular objectives for the overall metabolic network.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Furthermore, elementary mode analysis takes into account stoichiometrics and thermodynamics when evaluating whether a particular metabolic route or network is feasible and likely for a set of proteins/enzymes.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] In 2009, Larhlimi and Bockmayr presented a new approach called "minimal metabolic behaviors" for the analysis of metabolic networks.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Like elementary modes or extreme pathways, these are uniquely determined by the network, and yield a complete description of the flux cone.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] However, the new description is much more compact.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] In contrast with elementary modes and extreme pathways, which use an inner description based on generating vectors of the flux cone, MMBs are using an outer description of the flux cone.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] This approach is based on sets of non-negativity constraints.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] These can be identified with irreversible reactions, and thus have a direct biochemical interpretation.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] One can characterize a metabolic network by MMBs and the reversible metabolic space.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] A different technique to simulate the metabolic network is to perform flux balance analysis.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] This method uses linear programming, but in contrast to elementary mode analysis and extreme pathways, only a single solution results in the end.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Linear programming is usually used to obtain the maximum potential of the objective function that you are looking at, and therefore, when using flux balance analysis, a single solution is found to the optimization problem.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] In a flux balance analysis approach, exchange fluxes are assigned to those metabolites that enter or leave the particular network only.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Those metabolites that are consumed within the network are not assigned any exchange flux value.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Also, the exchange fluxes along with the enzymes can have constraints ranging from a negative to positive value (ex: -10 to 10).
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Furthermore, this particular approach can accurately define if the reaction stoichiometry is in line with predictions by providing fluxes for the balanced reactions.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Also, flux balance analysis can highlight the most effective and efficient pathway through the network in order to achieve a particular objective function.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] In addition, gene knockout studies can be performed using flux balance analysis.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The enzyme that correlates to the gene that needs to be removed is given a constraint value of 0.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Then, the reaction that the particular enzyme catalyzes is completely removed from the analysis.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] In order to perform a dynamic simulation with such a network it is necessary to construct an ordinary differential equation system that describes the rates of change in each metabolite's concentration or amount.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] To this end, a rate law, i.e., a kinetic equation that determines the rate of reaction based on the concentrations of all reactants is required for each reaction.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Software packages that include numerical integrators, such as COPASI or SBMLsimulator, are then able to simulate the system dynamics given an initial condition.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Often these rate laws contain kinetic parameters with uncertain values.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] In many cases it is desired to estimate these parameter values with respect to given time-series data of metabolite concentrations.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The system is then supposed to reproduce the given data.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] For this purpose the distance between the given data set and the result of the simulation, i.e., the numerically or in few cases analytically obtained solution of the differential equation system is computed.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The values of the parameters are then estimated to minimize this distance.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] One step further, it may be desired to estimate the mathematical structure of the differential equation system because the real rate laws are not known for the reactions within the system under study.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] To this end, the program SBMLsqueezer allows automatic creation of appropriate rate laws for all reactions with the network.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Synthetic accessibility is a simple approach to network simulation whose goal is to predict which metabolic gene knockouts are lethal.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] To simulate a gene knockout, the reactions enabled by the gene are removed from the network and the synthetic accessibility metric is recalculated.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] An increase in the total number of steps is predicted to cause lethality.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Wunderlich and Mirny showed this simple, parameter-free approach predicted knockout lethality in *E. coli* and *S. cerevisiae* as well as elementary mode analysis and flux balance analysis in a variety of media.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The results these experiments can uncover novel pathways and metabolic activities and decipher between discrepancies in previous experimental data.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] Metabolic network reconstructions and models are used to understand how an organism or parasite functions inside of the host cell.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] For example, if the parasite serves to compromise the immune system by lysing macrophages, then the goal of metabolic reconstruction/simulation would be to determine the metabolites that are essential to the organism's proliferation inside of macrophages.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] If the proliferation cycle is inhibited, then the parasite would not continue to evade the host's immune system.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] A reconstruction model serves as a first step to deciphering the complicated mechanisms surrounding disease.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] These models can also look at the minimal genes necessary for a cell to maintain virulence.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-network-modelling] The next step would be to use the predictions and postulates generated from a reconstruction model and apply it to discover novel biological functions such as drug-engineering and drug delivery techniques.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] In biochemistry, a **metabolic pathway** is a linked series of chemical reactions occurring within a cell.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The reactants, products, and intermediates of an enzymatic reaction are known as metabolites, which are modified by a sequence of chemical reactions catalyzed by enzymes.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] In most cases of a metabolic pathway, the product of one enzyme acts as the substrate for the next.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] However, side products are considered waste and removed from the cell.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Different metabolic pathways function in the position within a eukaryotic cell and the significance of the pathway in the given compartment of the cell.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] For instance, the electron transport chain and oxidative phosphorylation all take place in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] In contrast, glycolysis, pentose phosphate pathway, and fatty acid biosynthesis all occur in the cytosol of a cell.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] There are two types of metabolic pathways that are characterized by their ability to either synthesize molecules with the utilization of energy (anabolic pathway), or break down complex molecules and release energy in the process (catabolic pathway).
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The two pathways complement each other in that the energy released from one is used up by the other.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The degradative process of a catabolic pathway provides the energy required to conduct the biosynthesis of an anabolic pathway.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] In addition to the two distinct metabolic pathways is the amphibolic pathway, which can be either catabolic or anabolic based on the need for or the availability of energy.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Pathways are required for the maintenance of homeostasis within an organism and the flux of metabolites through a pathway is regulated depending on the needs of the cell and the availability of the substrate.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The end product of a pathway may be used immediately, initiate another metabolic pathway or be stored for later use.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The metabolism of a cell consists of an elaborate network of interconnected pathways that enable the synthesis and breakdown of molecules (anabolism and catabolism).
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Each metabolic pathway consists of a series of biochemical reactions that are connected by their intermediates: the products of one reaction are the substrates for subsequent reactions, and so on.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Metabolic pathways are often considered to flow in one direction.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Although all chemical reactions are technically reversible, conditions in the cell are often such that it is thermodynamically more favorable for flux to proceed in one direction of a reaction.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] For example, one pathway may be responsible for the synthesis of a particular amino acid, but the breakdown of that amino acid may occur via a separate and distinct pathway.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] One example of an exception to this "rule" is the metabolism of glucose.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Glycolysis results in the breakdown of glucose, but several reactions in the glycolysis pathway are reversible and participate in the re-synthesis of glucose (gluconeogenesis).
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] In times of excess lipid or protein energy sources, certain reactions in the glycolysis pathway may run in reverse to produce glucose 6-phosphate, which is then used for storage as glycogen or starch.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The net reaction is, therefore, thermodynamically favorable, for it results in a lower free energy for the final products.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] A catabolic pathway is an exergonic system that produces chemical energy in the form of ATP, GTP, NADH, NADPH, FADH2, etc. from energy containing sources such as carbohydrates, fats, and proteins.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The end products are often carbon dioxide, water, and ammonia.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Coupled with an endergonic reaction of anabolism, the cell can synthesize new macromolecules using the original precursors of the anabolic pathway.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] An example of a coupled reaction is the phosphorylation of fructose-6-phosphate to form the intermediate fructose-1,6-bisphosphate by the enzyme phosphofructokinase accompanied by the hydrolysis of ATP in the pathway of glycolysis.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The resulting chemical reaction within the metabolic pathway is highly thermodynamically favorable and, as a result, irreversible in the cell.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] A core set of energy-producing catabolic pathways occur within all living organisms in some form.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] These pathways transfer the energy released by breakdown of nutrients into ATP and other small molecules used for energy (e.g.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] All cells can perform anaerobic respiration by glycolysis.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Additionally, most organisms can perform more efficient aerobic respiration through the citric acid cycle and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Additionally plants, algae and cyanobacteria are able to use sunlight to anabolically synthesize compounds from non-living matter by photosynthesis.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] In contrast to catabolic pathways, **anabolic pathways** require an energy input to construct macromolecules such as polypeptides, nucleic acids, proteins, polysaccharides, and lipids.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The isolated reaction of anabolism is unfavorable in a cell due to a positive Gibbs free energy (+Δ*G*).
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Thus, an input of chemical energy through a coupling with an exergonic reaction is necessary.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The coupled reaction of the catabolic pathway affects the thermodynamics of the reaction by lowering the overall activation energy of an anabolic pathway and allowing the reaction to take place.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Otherwise, an endergonic reaction is non-spontaneous.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] An anabolic pathway is a biosynthetic pathway, meaning that it combines smaller molecules to form larger and more complex ones.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] An example is the reversed pathway of glycolysis, otherwise known as gluconeogenesis, which occurs in the liver and sometimes in the kidney to maintain proper glucose concentration in the blood and supply the brain and muscle tissues with adequate amount of glucose.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Although gluconeogenesis is similar to the reverse pathway of glycolysis, it contains four distinct enzymes(pyruvate carboxylase, phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase, fructose 1,6-bisphosphatase, glucose 6-phosphatase) from glycolysis that allow the pathway to occur spontaneously.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] An **amphibolic pathway** is one that can be either catabolic or anabolic based on the availability of or the need for energy.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The currency of energy in a biological cell is adenosine triphosphate (ATP), which stores its energy in the phosphoanhydride bonds.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The energy is utilized to conduct biosynthesis, facilitate movement, and regulate active transport inside of the cell.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Examples of amphibolic pathways are the citric acid cycle and the glyoxylate cycle.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] These sets of chemical reactions contain both energy producing and utilizing pathways.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] To the right is an illustration of the amphibolic properties of the TCA cycle.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The glyoxylate shunt pathway is an alternative to the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle, for it redirects the pathway of TCA to prevent full oxidation of carbon compounds, and to preserve high energy carbon sources as future energy sources.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] This pathway occurs only in plants and bacteria and transpires in the absence of glucose molecules.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The flux of the entire pathway is regulated by the rate-determining steps.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] These are the slowest steps in a network of reactions.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The rate-limiting step occurs near the beginning of the pathway and is regulated by feedback inhibition, which ultimately controls the overall rate of the pathway.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The metabolic pathway in the cell is regulated by covalent or non-covalent modifications.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] A covalent modification involves an addition or removal of a chemical bond, whereas a non-covalent modification (also known as allosteric regulation) is the binding of the regulator to the enzyme via hydrogen bonds, electrostatic interactions, and Van der Waals forces.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The rate of turnover in a metabolic pathway, also known as the metabolic flux, is regulated based on the stoichiometric reaction model, the utilization rate of metabolites, and the translocation pace of molecules across the lipid bilayer.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The regulation methods are based on experiments involving 13C-labeling, which is then analyzed by nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) or gas chromatography–mass spectrometry (GC–MS)–derived mass compositions.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The aforementioned techniques synthesize a statistical interpretation of mass distribution in proteinogenic amino acids to the catalytic activities of enzymes in a cell.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Metabolic pathways can be targeted for clinically therapeutic uses.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Within the mitochondrial metabolic network, for instance, there are various pathways that can be targeted by compounds to prevent cancer cell proliferation.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] One such pathway is oxidative phosphorylation (OXPHOS) within the electron transport chain (ETC).
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Various inhibitors can downregulate the electrochemical reactions that take place at Complex I, II, III, and IV, thereby preventing the formation of an electrochemical gradient and downregulating the movement of electrons through the ETC.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The substrate-level phosphorylation that occurs at ATP synthase can also be directly inhibited, preventing the formation of ATP that is necessary to supply energy for cancer cell proliferation.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Some of these inhibitors, such as lonidamine and atovaquone, which inhibit Complex II and Complex III, respectively, are currently undergoing clinical trials for FDA approval.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Other non-FDA-approved inhibitors have still shown experimental success in vitro.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Heme, an important prosthetic group present in Complexes I, II, and IV can also be targeted, since heme biosynthesis and uptake have been correlated with increased cancer progression.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Various molecules can inhibit heme via different mechanisms.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] For instance, succinylacetone has been shown to decrease heme concentrations by inhibiting δ-aminolevulinic acid in murine erythroleukemia cells.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The primary structure of heme-sequestering peptides, such as HSP1 and HSP2, can be modified to downregulate heme concentrations and reduce proliferation of non-small lung cancer cells.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The tricarboxylic acid cycle (TCA) and glutaminolysis can also be targeted for cancer treatment, since they are essential for the survival and proliferation of cancer cells.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Ivosidenib and enasidenib, two FDA-approved cancer treatments, can arrest the TCA cycle of cancer cells by inhibiting isocitrate dehydrogenase-1 (IDH1) and isocitrate dehydrogenase-2 (IDH2), respectively.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Ivosidenib is specific to acute myeloid leukemia (AML) and cholangiocarcinoma, whereas enasidenib is specific to just acute myeloid leukemia (AML).
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] In a clinical trial consisting of 185 adult patients with cholangiocarcinoma and an IDH-1 mutation, there was a statistically significant improvement (p<0.0001; HR: 0.37) in patients randomized to ivosidenib.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Still, some of the adverse side effects in these patients included fatigue, nausea, diarrhea, decreased appetite, ascites, and anemia.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] In a clinical trial consisting of 199 adult patients with AML and an IDH2 mutation, 23% of patients experienced complete response (CR) or complete response with partial hematologic recovery (CRh) lasting a median of 8.2 months while on enasidenib.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Of the 157 patients who required transfusion at the beginning of the trial, 34% no longer required transfusions during the 56-day time period on enasidenib.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Of the 42% of patients who did not require transfusions at the beginning of the trial, 76% still did not require a transfusion by the end of the trial.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Side effects of enasidenib included nausea, diarrhea, elevated bilirubin and, most notably, differentiation syndrome.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Glutaminase (GLS), the enzyme responsible for converting glutamine to glutamate via hydrolytic deamidation during the first reaction of glutaminolysis, can also be targeted.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] In recent years, many small molecules, such as azaserine, acivicin, and CB-839 have been shown to inhibit glutaminase, thus reducing cancer cell viability and inducing apoptosis in cancer cells.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Due to its effective antitumor ability in several cancer types such as ovarian, breast and lung cancers, CB-839 is the only GLS inhibitor currently undergoing clinical studies for FDA-approval.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] Many metabolic pathways are of commercial interest.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] For instance, the production of many antibiotics or other drugs requires complex pathways.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The pathways to produce such compounds can be transplanted into microbes or other more suitable organism for production purposes.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] For example, the world's supply of the anti-cancer drug vinblastine is produced by relatively ineffient extraction and purification of the precursors vindoline and catharanthine from the plant *Catharanthus roseus*, which are then chemically converted into vinblastine.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] The biosynthetic pathway to produce vinblastine, including 30 enzymatic steps, has been transferred into yeast cells which is a convenient system to grow in large amounts.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] With these genetic modifications yeast can use its own metabolites geranyl pyrophosphate and tryptophan to produce the precursors of catharanthine and vindoline.
[src:systems-biology/metabolic-pathway] This process required 56 genetic edits, including expression of 34 heterologous genes from plants in yeast cells.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] As a paradigm, systems biology is usually defined in antithesis to the so-called reductionist paradigm (biological organisation), although it is consistent with the scientific method.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] It requires that we develop ways of thinking about integration that are as rigorous as our reductionist programmes, but different. ...
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Since the objective is a model of the interactions in a system, the experimental techniques that most suit systems biology are those that are system-wide and attempt to be as complete as possible.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Therefore, multiomics (transcriptomics, metabolomics, proteomics, etc) and high-throughput techniques are used to collect quantitative data for the construction and validation of models.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] To tackle these challenges, systems biology must incorporate methods and approaches from various disciplines that have not traditionally interfaced with one another.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The emergence of multi-omics technologies has transformed systems biology by providing extensive datasets that cover different biological layers, including genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics, and metabolomics.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] These technologies enable the large-scale measurement of biomolecules, leading to a more profound comprehension of biological processes and interactions.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Increasingly, methods such as network analysis, machine learning, and pathway enrichment are utilized to integrate and interpret multi-omics data, thereby improving our understanding of biological functions and disease mechanisms.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] It is challenging to trace the origins and beginnings of systems biology.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] A comprehensive perspective on the human body was central to the medical practices of Greek, Roman, and East Asian traditions, where physicians and thinkers like Hippocrates believed that health and illness were linked to the equilibrium or disruption of bodily fluids known as humors.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] This holistic perspective persisted in the Western world throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, with prominent physiologists viewing the body as controlled by various systems, including the nervous system, the gastrointestinal system, and the cardiovascular system.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] In the latter half of the 20th century, however, this way of thinking was largely supplanted by reductionism: To grasp how the body functions properly, one needed to comprehend the role of each component, from tissues and cells to the complete set of intracellular molecular building blocks.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] In the 17th century, the triumphs of physics and the advancement of mechanical clockwork prompted a reductionist viewpoint in biology, interpreting organisms as intricate machines made up of simpler elements.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Jan Smuts (1870–1950), naturalist/philosopher and twice Prime Minister of South Africa, coined the commonly used term holism.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Whole systems such as cells, tissues, organisms, and populations were proposed to have unique (emergent) properties.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] It was impossible to try and reassemble the behavior of the whole from the properties of the individual components, and new technologies were necessary to define and understand the behavior of systems.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Even though reductionism and holism are often contrasted with one another, they can be synthesized.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] One must understand how organisms are built (reductionism), while it is just as important to understand why they are so arranged (systems; holism).
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Each provides useful insights and answers different questions.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] However, the study of biological systems requires knowledge about control and design paradigms, as well as principles of structural stability, resilience, and robustness that are not directly inferred from mechanistic information.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] More profound insight will be gained by employing computer modeling to overcome the complexity in biological systems.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Nevertheless, this perspective was consistently balanced by thinkers who underscored the significance of organization and emergent traits in living systems.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] This reductionist perspective has achieved remarkable success, and our understanding of biological processes has expanded with incredible speed and intensity.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] However, alongside these extraordinary advancements, science gradually came to understand that possessing complete information about molecular components alone would not suffice to elucidate the workings of life: the individual components rarely illustrate the function of a complex system.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] It is now commonly recognized that we need approaches for reconstructing integrated systems from their constituent parts and processes if we are to comprehend biological phenomena and manipulate them in a thoughtful, focused way.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] In 1968, the term "systems biology" was first introduced at a conference.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Those within the discipline soon recognized—and this understanding gradually became known to the wider public—that computational approaches were necessary to fully articulate the concepts and potential of systems biology.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Specifically, these techniques needed to view biological phenomena as complex, multi-layered, adaptive, and dynamic systems.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] They had to account for transformations and intricate nonlinearities, thereby allowing for the smooth integration of smaller models ("modules") into larger, well-organized assemblies of models within complex settings.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] It became clear that mathematics and computation were vital for these methods.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] An acceleration of systems understanding came with the publication of the first ground-breaking text compiling molecular, physiological, and anatomical individuality in animals, which has been described as a revolution.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] More scientists started working on integration of mathematical concepts to understand and solve biological problems.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Top-down systems biology identifies molecular interaction networks by analyzing the correlated behaviors observed in large-scale 'omics' studies.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] With the advent of 'omics', this top-down strategy has become a leading approach.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] It begins with an overarching perspective of the system's behavior – examining everything at once – by gathering genome-wide experimental data and seeks to unveil and understand biological mechanisms at a more granular level – specifically, the individual components and their interactions.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] These hypotheses then generate new predictions of correlations, which can be explored in subsequent experiments or through additional biochemical investigations.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The notable advantages of top-down systems biology lie in its potential to provide comprehensive (i.e., genome-wide) insights and its focus on the metabolome, fluxome, transcriptome, and/or proteome.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Top-down methods prioritize overall system states as influencing factors in models and the computational (or optimality) principles that govern the dynamics of the global system.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Bottom-up systems biology infers the functional characteristics that may arise from a subsystem characterized with a high degree of mechanistic detail using molecular techniques.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] This approach begins with the foundational elements by developing the interactive behavior (rate equation) of each component process (e.g., enzymatic processes) within a manageable portion of the system.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] It examines the mechanisms through which functional properties arise in the interactions of known components.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Subsequently, these formulations are combined to understand the behavior of the system.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The primary goal of this method is to integrate the pathway models into a comprehensive model representing the entire system - the top or whole.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] As research and understanding advance, these models are often expanded by incorporating additional processes with high mechanistic detail.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The bottom-up approach facilitates the integration and translation of drug-specific in vitro findings to the in vivo human context.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] This encompasses data collected during the early phases of drug development, such as safety evaluations.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Achieving this necessitates various models, ranging from single-cell to advanced three-dimensional (3D) multiphase models.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Numerous successful instances of applying physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) modeling in drug discovery and development have been documented in the literature.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] According to the interpretation of systems biology as using large data sets using interdisciplinary tools, a typical application is metabolomics, which is the complete set of all the metabolic products, metabolites, in the system at the organism, cell, or tissue level.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Items that may be a computer database include: phenomics, organismal variation in phenotype as it changes during its life span; genomics, organismal deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) sequence, including intra-organismal cell specific variation.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] (i.e., telomere length variation); epigenomics/epigenetics, organismal and corresponding cell specific transcriptomic regulating factors not empirically coded in the genomic sequence.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Sub disciplines include phosphoproteomics, glycoproteomics and other methods to detect chemically modified proteins; glycomics, organismal, tissue, or cell-level measurements of carbohydrates; lipidomics, organismal, tissue, or cell level measurements of lipids.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The molecular interactions within the cell are also studied, this is called interactomics.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] A discipline in this field of study is protein–protein interactions, although interactomics includes the interactions of other molecules.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Neuroelectrodynamics, where the computer's or a brain's computing function as a dynamic system is studied along with its (bio)physical mechanisms; and fluxomics, measurements of the rates of metabolic reactions in a biological system (cell, tissue, or organism).
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] In approaching a systems biology problem there are two main approaches.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] These are the top down and bottom up approach.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The top down approach takes as much of the system into account as possible and relies largely on experimental results.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The RNA-Seq technique is an example of an experimental top down approach.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Conversely, the bottom up approach is used to create detailed models while also incorporating experimental data.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] An example of the bottom up approach is the use of circuit models to describe a simple gene network.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Various technologies utilized to capture dynamic changes in mRNA, proteins, and post-translational modifications.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Mechanobiology, forces and physical properties at all scales, their interplay with other regulatory mechanisms; biosemiotics, analysis of the system of sign relations of an organism or other biosystems; Physiomics, a systematic study of physiome in biology.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Cancer systems biology is an example of the systems biology approach, which can be distinguished by the specific object of study (tumorigenesis and treatment of cancer).
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The long-term objective of the systems biology of cancer is ability to better diagnose cancer, classify it and better predict the outcome of a suggested treatment, which is a basis for personalized cancer medicine and virtual cancer patient in more distant prospective.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Significant efforts in computational systems biology of cancer have been made in creating realistic multi-scale *in silico* models of various tumours.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The systems biology approach often involves the development of mechanistic models, such as the reconstruction of dynamic systems from the quantitative properties of their elementary building blocks.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] For instance, a cellular network can be modelled mathematically using methods coming from chemical kinetics and control theory.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Due to the large number of parameters, variables and constraints in cellular networks, numerical and computational techniques are often used (e.g., flux balance analysis).
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Other aspects of computer science, informatics, and statistics are also used in systems biology.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Much of the analysis of genomic data sets also include identifying correlations.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Additionally, as much of the information comes from different fields, the development of syntactically and semantically sound ways of representing biological models is needed.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] A model serves as a conceptual depiction of objects or processes, highlighting certain characteristics of these items or activities.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] A model captures only certain facets of reality; however, when created correctly, this limited scope is adequate because the primary goal of modeling is to address specific inquiries.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The saying, "essentially, all models are wrong, but some are useful," attributed to the statistician George Box, is a suitable principle for constructing models.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Researchers begin by choosing a biological pathway and diagramming all of the protein, gene, and/or metabolic pathways.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] After determining all of the interactions, mass action kinetics or enzyme kinetic rate laws are used to describe the speed of the reactions in the system.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Using mass-conservation, the differential equations for the biological system can be constructed.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Experiments or parameter fitting can be done to determine the parameter values to use in the differential equations.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] These parameter values will be the various kinetic constants required to fully describe the model.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] This model determines the behavior of species in biological systems and bring new insight to the specific activities of systems.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Sometimes it is not possible to gather all reaction rates of a system.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Unknown reaction rates are determined by simulating the model of known parameters and target behavior which provides possible parameter values.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The use of constraint-based reconstruction and analysis (COBRA) methods has become popular among systems biologists to simulate and predict the metabolic phenotypes, using genome-scale models.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] One of the methods is the flux balance analysis (FBA) approach, by which one can study the biochemical networks and analyze the flow of metabolites through a particular metabolic network, by optimizing the objective function of interest (e.g. maximizing biomass production to predict growth).
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Systems biology, an interdisciplinary field that combines biology, data analysis, and mathematical modeling, has revolutionized various sectors, including medicine, agriculture, and environmental science.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] By integrating omics data (genomics, proteomics, metabolomics, etc.), systems biology provides a holistic understanding of complex biological systems, enabling advancements in drug discovery, crop improvement, and environmental impact assessment.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] This response explores the applications of systems biology across these domains, highlighting both industrial and academic research contributions.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] System biology is used in agriculture to identify the genetic and metabolic components of complex characteristics through trait dissection.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] It aids in the comprehension of plant-pathogen interactions in disease resistance.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] It is utilized in nutritional quality to enhance nutritional content through metabolic engineering.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Approaches to cancer systems biology have made it possible to effectively combine experimental data with computer algorithms and, as an exception, to apply actionable targeted medicines for the treatment of cancer.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] In order to apply innovative cancer systems biology techniques and boost their effectiveness for customizing new, individualized cancer treatment modalities, comprehensive multi-omics data acquired through the sequencing of tumor samples and experimental model systems will be crucial.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Cancer systems biology has the potential to provide insights into intratumor heterogeneity and identify therapeutic options.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] In particular, enhanced cancer systems biology methods that incorporate not only multi-omics data from tumors, but also extensive experimental models derived from patients can assist clinicians in their decision-making processes, ultimately aiming to address treatment failures in cancer.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Before the 1990s, phenotypic drug discovery formed the foundation of most research in drug discovery, utilizing cellular and animal disease models to find drugs without focusing on a specific molecular target.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] However, following the completion of the human genome project, target-based drug discovery has become the predominant approach in contemporary pharmaceutical research for various reasons.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Gene knockout and transgenic models enable researchers to investigate and gain insights into the function of targets and the mechanisms by which drugs operate on a molecular level.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Target-based assays lend themselves better to high-throughput screening, which simplifies the process of identifying second-generation drugs—those that improve upon first-in-class drugs in aspects such as potency, selectivity, and half-life, especially when combined with structure-based drug design.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] To do this, researchers utilize the three-dimensional structure of target proteins and computational models of interactions between small molecules and those targets to aid in the identification of superior compounds.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The multi-omics technologies in system biology can be also be used in aspects of food quality and safety.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] High-throughput omics techniques, including genomics, proteomics, and metabolomics, offer valuable insights into the molecular composition of food products, facilitating the identification of critical elements that affect food quality and safety.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] For example, integrating omics data can enhance the understanding of the metabolic pathways and associated functional gene patterns that contribute to both the nutritional value and safety of food crops.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] This comprehensive approach guarantees the creation of food products that are both nutritious and safe, capable of satisfying the increasing global demand.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Genomics examines all genes as an evolving system over time, aiming to understand their interactions and effects on biological pathways, networks, and physiology in a broader context compared to genetics.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] As a result, genomics holds significant potential for discovering clusters of genes associated with complex disorders, aiding in the comprehension and management of diseases induced by environmental factors.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] When exploring the interactions between the environment and the genome as contributors to complex diseases, it is clear that the genome itself cannot be altered for the time being.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] However, once these interactions are recognized, it is feasible to minimize exposure or adjust lifestyle factors related to the environmental aspect of the disease.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Gene-environment interactions can occur through direct associations with active metabolites at certain locations within the genome, potentially leading to mutations that could cause human diseases.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Indirect interactions with the human genome can take place through intracellular receptors that function as ligand-activated transcription factors, which modulate gene expression and maintain cellular balance, or with an environmental factor that may produce detrimental effects.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] This type of environmental-gene interaction could be more straightforward to investigate than direct interactions since there are numerous markers of this kind of interaction that are readily measurable before the disease manifests.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Examples of this include the expression of cytochrome P450 genes following exposure to environmental substances, such as the polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon benzo[a]pyrene, which binds to the Ah receptor.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] One of the main challenges in systems biology is the connection between experimental descriptions, observations, data, models, and the assumptions that stem from them.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] In essence, systems biology must be understood within an information management framework that significantly encompasses experimental life sciences.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Models are created using various languages or representation schemes, each suitable for conveying and reasoning about distinct sets of characteristics.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] There is no single universal language for systems biology that can adequately cover the diverse phenomena we aim to investigate.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] However, this intricate scenario overlooks two important aspects.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Models can be developed in multiple versions over time and by different research teams.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Conflicts can occur, and observations may be disputed.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Various researchers might produce models in different versions and configurations.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The unpredictable elements suggest that systems biology is not likely to yield a definitive collection of established models.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Instead, we can expect a rich ecosystem of models to develop within a structure that fosters discussion and cooperation among participants.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Challenges also exist in verifying the constraints and creating modeling frameworks with robust compositional strategies.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] This may create a need to handle models that may conflict with one another, whether between schemes or across different scales.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] In the end, the goal could involve the creation of personalized models that reflect differences in physiology, as opposed to universal models of biological processes.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Other challenges include the massive amount of data created by high-throughput omics technologies which presents considerable challenges in terms of computation and storage.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Each analysis in omics can result in data files ranging from terabytes to petabytes, which requires strong computational systems and ample storage solutions to manage and process these datasets effectively.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The computational requirements are made more difficult by the necessity for advanced algorithms that can integrate and analyze diverse, high-dimensional data.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Approaches like deep learning and network-based methods have displayed potential in tackling these issues, but they also demand significant computational power.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Utilizing AI in Systems Biology enables scientists to uncover novel insights into the intricate relationships present within biological systems, such as those among genes, proteins, and cells.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] A significant focus within Systems Biology is the application of AI for the analysis of expansive and complex datasets, including multi-omics data produced by high-throughput methods like next-generation sequencing and proteomics.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Approaches powered by AI can be employed to detect patterns and correlations within these datasets and to anticipate the behavior of biological systems under varying conditions.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] For instance, artificial intelligence can identify genes that are expressed differently across various cancer types or detect small molecules linked to particular disease states.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] A key difficulty in analyzing multi-omics data is the integration of information from multiple sources.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] AI can create integrative models that consider the intricate interactions between different types of molecular data.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] These models may be utilized to uncover new biomarkers or therapeutic targets for diseases, as well as to enhance our understanding of fundamental biological processes.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] By significantly speeding up our comprehension of complex biological systems, AI has the potential to lead to new treatments and therapies for a range of diseases.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] Structural systems biology is a multidisciplinary field that merges systems biology with structural biology to investigate biological systems at the molecular scale.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] This domain strives for a thorough understanding of how biological molecules interact and function within cells, tissues, and organisms.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] The integration of AI in structural systems biology has become increasingly vital for examining extensive and complex datasets and modeling the behavior of biological systems.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] AI facilitates the analysis of protein–protein interaction networks within structural systems biology.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] These networks can be explored using graph theory and various mathematical methods, uncovering key characteristics such as hubs and modules.
[src:systems-biology/systems-biology] AI can also assist in the discovery of new drugs or therapies by predicting the effect of a drug on a particular biological component or pathway.
